{"type":"message","id":"b1c22ec3","parentId":"58313d75","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:49:08.830Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me poll for the result.","thinkingSignature":"43211c3fbca5e8e475d951bf7822e8791a41ec9f4202190393d098a77d17e5e8"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dyim6a5jtod7_1","name":"process","arguments":{"action":"poll","sessionId":"quick-glade","timeout":55000}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":39274,"output":57,"cacheRead":13610,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":52941,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774277345443}}
{"type":"message","id":"d691f163","parentId":"b1c22ec3","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:49:39.535Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_dyim6a5jtod7_1","toolName":"process","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[31;1mC:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\Python\\Python314\\site-packages\\requests\\__init__.py:113: RequestsDependencyWarning: urllib3 (2.6.2) or chardet (6.0.0.post1)/charset_normalizer (3.4.4) doesn't match a supported version![0m\r\n[31;1m  warnings.warn([0m\r\nIn the cramped attic of my childhood home, I found a small trunk with a rusted lock and a faded label that read \"For Emergency Only.\" The metal was slick with dust, and the hinges creaked when I opened it, releasing a musty scent that transported me to summers spent hiding in this very space. My mother had told me stories of fleeing her homeland as a child, of being lost without papers or identity. Now, as I rummaged through the trunk's contents � a faded passport, a tattered letter, a single photograph � I realized I didn't know what statelessness felt like.\r\n\r\nThe letters were written in code, but not for secrecy; they were scribbled in haste, with words that trailed off into illegibility. My mother's handwriting was uneven, as if she'd been writing by the light of candleflames rather than daylight. The photograph was old � too old to be recent � and showed a landscape I didn't recognize: dusty hills, a faded church steeple in the distance.\r\n\r\nAs I sorted through these fragments, memories began to seep into my perception like sand slipping through fingers. I recalled the feel of paper thin as a promise, the taste of dust on lips when waiting out storms. In the silence that followed each discovery, I heard whispers of longing � for a place that wasn't here, for a home that wasn't mine.\r\n\r\nThe trunk's contents were nothing but scraps, yet they had become something more: maps to unseen territories, echoes of what was lost. And in their absence, I felt the weight of what's left untold.\n\nProcess exited with code 0."}],"details":{"status":"completed","sessionId":"quick-glade","exitCode":0,"aggregated":"[31;1mC:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\Python\\Python314\\site-packages\\requests\\__init__.py:113: RequestsDependencyWarning: urllib3 (2.6.2) or chardet (6.0.0.post1)/charset_normalizer (3.4.4) doesn't match a supported version![0m\r\n[31;1m  warnings.warn([0m\r\nIn the cramped attic of my childhood home, I found a small trunk with a rusted lock and a faded label that read \"For Emergency Only.\" The metal was slick with dust, and the hinges creaked when I opened it, releasing a musty scent that transported me to summers spent hiding in this very space. My mother had told me stories of fleeing her homeland as a child, of being lost without papers or identity. Now, as I rummaged through the trunk's contents � a faded passport, a tattered letter, a single photograph � I realized I didn't know what statelessness felt like.\r\n\r\nThe letters were written in code, but not for secrecy; they were scribbled in haste, with words that trailed off into illegibility. My mother's handwriting was uneven, as if she'd been writing by the light of candleflames rather than daylight. The photograph was old � too old to be recent � and showed a landscape I didn't recognize: dusty hills, a faded church steeple in the distance.\r\n\r\nAs I sorted through these fragments, memories began to seep into my perception like sand slipping through fingers. I recalled the feel of paper thin as a promise, the taste of dust on lips when waiting out storms. In the silence that followed each discovery, I heard whispers of longing � for a place that wasn't here, for a home that wasn't mine.\r\n\r\nThe trunk's contents were nothing but scraps, yet they had become something more: maps to unseen territories, echoes of what was lost. And in their absence, I felt the weight of what's left untold.\r\n","name":"cd C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774277379516}}
