{"type":"message","id":"4618d61b","parentId":"edaed180","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:31:39.921Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still not working correctly. All literary concepts have exactly 0.576 — still equalized. The issue is that with `literary` domain, the goal_clusters are `[\"creative\", \"literary\"]`, but the goal concepts from `build_thematic_graph` are ALL concepts in those clusters. Then in `run_drift`, goal concepts are seeded at 0.95 and their cluster-mates at 0.5. The literary cluster has many concepts so they all get 0.95 initially, then diffuse/decay/re-boost...\n\nWait — the issue is that the literary cluster has 30 concepts and all of them are seeded at 0.95. \n\nAfter one diffusion step with 133 nodes and ~8 within-cluster connections each, the 30 literary nodes at 0.95 spread their activation across each other and incoming activation from other nodes, converging to that 0.576 equilibrium. The re-boost kicks in every 4 steps at 0.6 for goal clusters, which falls below the equilibrium anyway, so nothing meaningful happens. I need to think about this differently — the real problem is that the literary cluster is too large and too internally connected, so the equalization is inevitable.\n\nWhat if I seed only a random subset of goal concepts at 0.95 instead of all of them? Or better yet, what if I don't rebuild the graph through run_drift at all and instead use the concept graph directly with much stronger differentiation in the initial activations? Actually, I'm realizing the core issue might be that a 133-node sparse graph with max 8 connections per node still isn't sparse enough to prevent this kind of averaging. Let me look at what demo.py actually does — it uses the same sparse adjacency and goal concept approach, but those concepts are spread across 5-8 clusters, not concentrated in one.\n\nI see it now: in demo.py, \"creative\" is a single concept in a cluster that contains many other concepts, so only that one concept gets seeded at 0.95 while its cluster-mates sit at 0.5. But in my literary domain setup, the \"literary\" cluster is the goal cluster itself, which means all 30 concepts in that cluster get seeded at 0.95 — and that's way too much. The fix is to make the initial seeding more selective by picking just the top-k concepts in the goal cluster to receive the high activation, rather than the entire cluster.\n\nActually, the cleaner approach is to shift the re-boost strategy: instead of broadly boosting entire goal clusters every 4 steps, I should only boost the top concepts that have already drifted above a certain threshold. This way, concepts that are genuinely activating get reinforced, while weaker activations don't get artificially propped up just because they're in a goal cluster.","thinkingSignature":"fe154db671dda55a3b87894ee7ad44d34d06408406bba4bedc89a853cb0326f5"},{"type":"text","text":"The literary cluster is too big (30 concepts all seeded at 0.95). Let me fix the seeding to pick just a subset:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_n65n4h4nw54i_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\Claw\\projects\\spark\\core\\engine.py","oldText":"def run_drift(\n    graph: ConceptGraph,\n    concept_to_cluster: Dict[str, str],\n    goal_concepts: List[str],\n    steering: float = 0.3,\n    steps: int = 30,\n    seed: int = 42,\n) -> Tuple[ConceptGraph, List[ConceptNode]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Run the drift dynamics on a pre-built graph.\n\n    Args:\n        graph: built concept graph\n        concept_to_cluster: cluster mapping\n        goal_concepts: specific concepts to steer toward (from primary clusters)\n        steering: 0.0 (pure drift) → 1.0 (pure steering)\n        steps: number of drift cycles\n        seed: random seed\n\n    Returns:\n        graph: graph with updated activations\n        history: list of node snapshots per step (last step)\n    \"\"\"\n    goal_concepts_set = set(goal_concepts)\n    goal_clusters = {concept_to_cluster.get(c, \"\") for c in goal_concepts_set}\n\n    # Differentiated seeding: goal concepts get 0.95, their cluster-mates 0.5, rest 0.05\n    for node in graph.nodes.values():\n        if node.id in goal_concepts_set:\n            node.activation = 0.95\n        else:\n            cid = concept_to_cluster.get(node.id, \"\")\n            node.activation = 0.5 if cid in goal_clusters else 0.05\n\n    config = DriftChamberConfig(\n        steering_strength=steering,\n        diffusion_rate=0.1,\n        decay_rate=0.02,\n        seed=seed,\n        max_steps=steps,\n    )\n\n    history = []\n    for step in range(steps):\n        _, graph = drift_cycle(graph, None, config)\n        graph = decay(graph, rate=0.02)\n\n        # Periodic re-boost: every 4 steps, reinforce goal clusters against decay\n        if step > 0 and step % 4 == 0 and steering > 0:\n            for node in graph.nodes.values():\n                cid = concept_to_cluster.get(node.id, \"\")\n                if cid in goal_clusters:\n                    node.activation = max(node.activation, 0.6)\n\n        if step == steps - 1:\n            history = [n for n in graph.nodes.values()]\n\n    return graph, history","newText":"def run_drift(\n    graph: ConceptGraph,\n    concept_to_cluster: Dict[str, str],\n    goal_concepts: List[str],\n    steering: float = 0.3,\n    steps: int = 30,\n    seed: int = 42,\n) -> Tuple[ConceptGraph, List[ConceptNode]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Run the drift dynamics on a pre-built graph.\n\n    Goal concepts are seeded at 0.95. If there are too many (e.g. >10),\n    a random subset is chosen to prevent cluster-wide equalization.\n    The re-boost also targets only surviving high-activation concepts.\n    \"\"\"\n    import random\n    random.seed(seed)\n\n    goal_concepts_set = set(goal_concepts)\n    goal_clusters = {concept_to_cluster.get(c, \"\") for c in goal_concepts_set}\n\n    # Limit high-activation seed to at most 8 concepts to avoid equalization\n    seed_concepts = list(goal_concepts_set)\n    random.shuffle(seed_concepts)\n    seed_concepts = set(seed_concepts[:8])\n\n    for node in graph.nodes.values():\n        if node.id in seed_concepts:\n            node.activation = 0.95\n        else:\n            cid = concept_to_cluster.get(node.id, \"\")\n            node.activation = 0.4 if cid in goal_clusters else 0.05\n\n    config = DriftChamberConfig(\n        steering_strength=steering,\n        diffusion_rate=0.1,\n        decay_rate=0.02,\n        seed=seed,\n        max_steps=steps,\n    )\n\n    history = []\n    for step in range(steps):\n        _, graph = drift_cycle(graph, None, config)\n        graph = decay(graph, rate=0.02)\n\n        # Re-boost every 4 steps: only concepts that SURVIVED above threshold\n        if step > 0 and step % 4 == 0 and steering > 0:\n            for node in graph.nodes.values():\n                if node.activation > 0.35:\n                    cid = concept_to_cluster.get(node.id, \"\")\n                    if cid in goal_clusters:\n                        node.activation = max(node.activation, 0.65)\n\n        if step == steps - 1:\n            history = [n for n in graph.nodes.values()]\n\n    return graph, history"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":68091,"output":1618,"cacheRead":13610,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":83319,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774279866171}}
