{"type":"message","id":"4f7d997f","parentId":"974d0815","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:31:59.033Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still equalized — all the literary concepts at 0.622. The problem is clear: these 30 literary concepts are all connected to each other within the cluster (WITHIN_CLUSTER_WEIGHT = 0.85, MAX_WITHIN_K = 8). With 8 edges per node within the literary cluster, they keep reinforcing each other. The seed concepts get boosted, spread activation to 8 neighbors, and after 30 steps everything in that dense cluster converges to the same level.\n\nThe real fix: the literary cluster shouldn't have so many concepts all connected to each other. The within-cluster edges should be sparser, or the concepts should come from diverse clusters.\n \nI'm realizing the actual issue — the literary cluster has 30 concepts all at the same activation level because they're densely interconnected. The demo.py approach works because its goal clusters are sparse by design. With 8 random seed concepts spreading activation across 30 densely connected nodes, they all converge to equilibrium. I need to either thin out the literary cluster's internal connections or ensure the seed concepts are already naturally differentiated through the graph structure itself.\n\nBut actually, the real question is whether this even matters for the API. The text generation still works fine with these activations, so maybe I'm overthinking the technical details here.","thinkingSignature":"23f04b7b5491d9b0d8c8f08c987b969c84d9a52b1d5e76882db914a1347ea40a"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me step back and test with the `all` domain where the goal clusters are more distributed:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dech38ppr52z_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\Claw\\projects\\spark && python -c \"\nimport sys\nsys.path.insert(0, '.')\nsys.path.insert(0, '..')\nfrom spark.core.engine import spark_drift\nfor domain in ['all', 'literary'