{"type":"message","id":"edbbc315","parentId":"5fcdda63","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:32:30.817Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so `all` domain works well: top concepts are differentiated, tensions fire, strong=8. The `literary` domain is the problem because the literary cluster is internally dense (all literary devices connected to each other).\n\nThe fundamental issue is that the literary cluster has many concepts that are semantically similar (all literary devices like foreshadowing, flashback, unreliable_narrator, etc.) and they form a tight cluster within which activation equalizes.\n\nLet me fix this at the source — in the adjacency building for the literary cluster, don't add within-cluster edges for the literary cluster. Or reduce MAX_WITHIN_K significantly for literary. Actually, I can just exclude the \"literary\" cluster from within-cluster edges by not adding them in the adjacency builder. \n\nBut wait, this is a domain-specific hack. The real issue is that the concept graph itself isn't structured right for literary — all the literary devices are too semantically similar, so when activation spreads through the within-cluster edges, they all converge to the same value. I need to either make the literary cluster sparser by limiting within-cluster edges more aggressively, or exclude it entirely from within-cluster connectivity and rely only on cross-cluster edges to differentiate concepts.\n\nLet me try removing within-cluster edges for the literary cluster entirely — this forces literary concepts to only connect to other clusters through cross-cluster edges, which should give them more varied activation patterns. Though this might leave some literary nodes with no edges at all if there aren't enough cross-cluster connections...\n\nActually, looking at the literary cluster (32 concepts), with MAX_CROSS_K=4, each concept could have up to 4 cross-cluster edges. The real question is which cross-cluster connections are actually defined in CROSS_WEIGHTS for literary. From the thematic_graph.py: `(\"literary\", \"creative\", 0.5)` — so literary connects to creative with weight 0.5. But creative itself might be too broad, which is why all the literary concepts are still converging at the same activation level.\n\nThe core issue is that concept domains with large, semantically dense clusters (literary=32, emotions=~50) will inevitably equalize because every node connects to every other node within the cluster. To fix this properly would require embedding-based similarity scoring like build_graph.py does, which is much more sophisticated than the current thematic approach.\n\nBut there's a simpler solution: the `all` domain actually works well with 8 strong concepts and tensions firing, which is exactly what persona.py uses. So I should just deprioritize fixing literary and instead focus on getting the API functional. Though for the API itself, even the equalized literary result is still useful for text generation since the concept list gets passed to the LLM either way — and the LLM can generate coherent text from any concept cluster, even if they're clustered together.","thinkingSignature":"7414cb71f44f94d1b8c4dc1d360dbf2e9aafe9946e984f26ecd1af7afe5d220c"},{"type":"text","text":"The `all` domain works great. The literary cluster is too internally dense (32 literary devices all connected to each other, equalize every time). That's a graph topology issue. The fix is to just not add within-cluster edges for the literary cluster:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qzxgb9kdi6o1_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\Claw\\projects\\spark\\core\\engine.py","oldText":"        # Within-cluster edges\n        within = [\n            (c2, 1.0 if (c1, c2) in TENSION_SET or (c2, c1) in TENSION_SET else 0.5)\n            for c2 in selected\n            if c1 != c2 and concept_to_cluster.get(c2) == ca\n        ]\n        within.sort(key=lambda x: -x[1])\n        for c2, _ in within[:MAX_WITHIN_K]:\n            adj[(c1, c2)] = WITHIN_CLUSTER_WEIGHT","newText":"        # Within-cluster edges — skip \"literary\" cluster (too many similar concepts = equalization)\n        within = [\n            (c2, 1.0 if (c1, c2) in TENSION_SET or (c2, c1) in TENSION_SET else 0.5)\n            for c2 in selected\n            if c1 != c2 and concept_to_cluster.get(c2) == ca and ca != \"literary\"\n        ]\n        within.sort(key=lambda x: -x[1])\n        for c2, _ in within[:MAX_WITHIN_K]:\n            adj[(c1, c2)] = WITHIN_CLUSTER_WEIGHT"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":71070,"output":945,"cacheRead":13610,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":85625,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774279927011}}
